                <h1 class="article-title">Not Just Transformers - Discover the Highlights of the 2026 Taipei Lantern Festival at Taipei Expo Park</h1>
                <div class="article-meta">
                    <span>2026.02.20</span>
                    <span>Issued by: The Department of Transportation, Taipei City Government</span>
                </div>
            </header>

            <div class="article-body">
                <img src="../images/news/n260126_01.jpg" alt="News Image">

                <p>
                    The “2026 Taipei Lantern Festival” will take place from February 25 to March 15 across the Taipei Expo Park Area and the Ximen Area. This year marks the festival’s first-ever “Two Areas, Two IPs” curatorial format, presenting beloved pop culture icons alongside imaginative artistic creations to deliver an unprecedented citywide spectacle of light and shadow. Beyond the highly anticipated Transformers lantern installations, the Taipei Expo Park Area also features a rich lineup of artist-designed works and an internationally inspired Friendship Lantern Zone, inviting visitors to immerse themselves in a dazzling urban celebration.
                </p>

                <p>
                    This year, the Taipei Expo Park Area welcomes participation from 13 countries and international cities in the Friendship Lantern Zone. The American Institute in Taiwan joins for the first time to commemorate the 250th anniversary of the United States, alongside distinctive lantern displays from Daegu, South Korea, and Hirosaki in Aomori, Japan. Visitors can experience global light art and cultural exchange without leaving Taiwan.
                </p>

                <p>
                    Another major highlight is the “Team Taipei Bravo Bear” lantern series representing all 12 administrative districts. Taipei’s beloved mascot Bravo Bear transforms into a district ambassador for each area, debuting 12 exclusive new looks that incorporate distinctive local characteristics. Together they form a spirited city lineup themed “Every District, Every Bravo.” In Xinyi District, Bravo Bear appears in glamorous stage attire, microphone in hand, channeling the energy of a rock superstar, a playful nod to the district’s fashionable urban image and the concert buzz surrounding the Taipei Dome. In Zhongshan District, the mascot sports trendy autumn and winter fashion while holding an EasyCard, evoking leisurely MRT rides through the Zhongshan shopping district and strolls along the Linear Park, perfectly reflecting the district’s blend of commercial vitality and creative flair. In Beitou District, Bravo Bear relaxes in a steaming hot spring tub with an adorably blissful expression, as if genuinely savoring the soothing warmth of Beitou’s famed hot springs. Visitors are warmly invited to meet the most charming representatives of each district.
                </p>

                <img src="../images/news/n260220-1_01.jpg" alt="News Image">

                <p>
                    The Artist Lantern Zone at the Taipei Expo Park Area is equally rich in creativity and interactive appeal. Just outside MRT Yuanshan Station stands “TreeLink” by Kai-wei Chen, inspired by Taipei’s iconic banyan trees. The installation connects symbolic imagery from participating friendship cities along its illuminated branches, forming a radiant tree that represents openness and international exchange. Yu-chia Chang’s “Gymnastics Baron” portrays a futuristic astronaut gazing into the starry sky, highlighting the dynamic interplay between technology and art. Chih-ming Hsu’s “Forest Light Pathway” creates a breathing-like, empathetic experience through the interaction of light and footsteps. Chieh-sen Chiu’s “BASE” transforms the urban night skyline into a luminous illusion, reinterpreting city order and sensory memory. Designed by the Guzao Music(穀造音樂) team, “Whimsy Fizzy Rhapsody” gathers a cast of adorable creature characters and integrates interactive technology with floating bubble effects, inviting visitors into a playful sensory dialogue. Meanwhile, Margot Guillemot’s “SPACE TAIPEI” traces the flight path of a paper airplane in beams of light, symbolizing Taipei’s courage to break boundaries and its readiness to take flight. Interwoven with the IP lantern installations, these artistic creations shape a diverse, fantastical, and forward-looking atmosphere throughout the Taipei Expo Park Area.
                </p>

                <p>
                    The Taipei Expo Park Area of the 2026 Taipei Lantern Festival will run from February 25 to March 15, with daily illumination from 17:00 to 22:00. The Optimus Prime main lantern show begins at 18:00 and takes place every 30 minutes. To ensure a comfortable viewing environment, smoking is prohibited within the exhibition areas and surrounding zones during the festival. Visitors who wish to smoke are advised to use designated smoking areas.
                </p>

                <p>
                    Surrounded by vibrant shopping districts, temples, Dalong Street Night Market, Shilin Night Market, and Yangmingshan, the Taipei Expo Park Area offers convenient access to a full Taipei itinerary that combines “flower viewing, lantern appreciation, and neighborhood exploration.” In addition to traveling via MRT to Yuanshan Station, visitors are also encouraged to take the MRT to Zhongshan Elementary School Station, explore the Zhongshan shopping district, admire the lantern decorations at Jingfu Temple, and then continue on to Yuanshan Expo Park. The Department of Information and Tourism warmly invites visitors from across Taiwan to plan their trips early during the Lunar New Year holiday and experience firsthand the creativity and technological brilliance of the 2026 Taipei Lantern Festival at the Taipei Expo Park Area, sharing in the radiant anticipation of the Lantern Festival with family and friends.
                </p>

